<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,358,2041]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,610,637]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[332,563,611,637]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[332,563,611,637]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ceroptres cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically almost identical to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ashmead, 1896" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[1027,1367,611,637]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis box="[1027,1174,611,637]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. frondosae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ashmead, W. H." box="[1184,1367,611,637]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="179 - 234" refId="ref55364" refString="Ashmead, W. H. (1896) Descriptions of new parasitic Hymenoptera. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 23 (2), 179 - 234." type="journal article" year="1896">Ashmead, 1896</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from which differs only by having POL about 2.0 times as long as OOL (
<figureCitation box="[918,1000,647,673]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1439,1464]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female faces of valid species of Ceroptres: a) C. catesbaei (type); b) C. cerri; c) C. clavicornis; d) C. confertus (type); e) C. cornigera (type); f) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. cornigera; g) head of C. cornigera in dorsal view; h) C. ensiger; i) C. frondosae (type); j) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. frondosae; k) head of C. frondosae in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772837/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[972,1000,647,673]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="g" value="3.0">3g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
) (POL 3.0 times as long as OOL in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. frondosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation box="[277,357,683,710]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1439,1464]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female faces of valid species of Ceroptres: a) C. catesbaei (type); b) C. cerri; c) C. clavicornis; d) C. confertus (type); e) C. cornigera (type); f) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. cornigera; g) head of C. cornigera in dorsal view; h) C. ensiger; i) C. frondosae (type); j) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. frondosae; k) head of C. frondosae in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772837/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 3k</figureCitation>
) and OOL 1.5 or more times as long as diameter of lateral ocelli (
<figureCitation box="[1104,1186,683,709]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1439,1464]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female faces of valid species of Ceroptres: a) C. catesbaei (type); b) C. cerri; c) C. clavicornis; d) C. confertus (type); e) C. cornigera (type); f) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. cornigera; g) head of C. cornigera in dorsal view; h) C. ensiger; i) C. frondosae (type); j) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. frondosae; k) head of C. frondosae in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772837/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1157,1186,683,709]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="g" value="3.0">3g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
) (subequal in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. frondosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation box="[231,315,719,746]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1439,1464]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female faces of valid species of Ceroptres: a) C. catesbaei (type); b) C. cerri; c) C. clavicornis; d) C. confertus (type); e) C. cornigera (type); f) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. cornigera; g) head of C. cornigera in dorsal view; h) C. ensiger; i) C. frondosae (type); j) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. frondosae; k) head of C. frondosae in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772837/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 3k</figureCitation>
). It also has a medial ridge in the depressed area delimited by the two vertical carinae on the lower face (
<figureCitation box="[215,296,755,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1439,1464]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female faces of valid species of Ceroptres: a) C. catesbaei (type); b) C. cerri; c) C. clavicornis; d) C. confertus (type); e) C. cornigera (type); f) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. cornigera; g) head of C. cornigera in dorsal view; h) C. ensiger; i) C. frondosae (type); j) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. frondosae; k) head of C. frondosae in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772837/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 3f</figureCitation>
), being almost the only species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartig" authorityYear="1840" box="[696,806,755,781]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[696,806,755,781]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ceroptres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with this trait, except for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[1108,1224,755,781]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Amblynotus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ensiger">
<emphasis box="[1108,1224,755,781]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. ensiger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[1283,1428,755,781]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis box="[1283,1428,755,781]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. frondosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[261,376,791,817]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Amblynotus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ensiger">
<emphasis box="[261,376,791,817]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. ensiger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the mesopleuron anteriorly alutaceous (
<figureCitation box="[873,955,791,818]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1924,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 6. a) Ceroptres cornigera lateral and b) dorsal habitus (type); c) C. ensiger lateral habitus, d) detail of mesopleuron and e) dorsal habitus (type); f) C. frondosae lateral and g) dorsal habitus (type); h) head and mesosoma of C. kovalevi in lateral view, i) lateral metasoma and j) head and mesosoma in dorsal view (type)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772846/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 6d</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[1019,1163,791,817]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis box="[1019,1163,791,817]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. frondosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has different POL/OOL and OOL/diameter of lateral ocelli ratios as stated above.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,358,2041]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,434,862,889]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Brief redescription.</emphasis>
Apart from the morphological traits mentioned in the diagnosis section, 
<taxonomicName box="[1264,1409,863,889]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[1264,1409,863,889]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also characterized by having female antenna 12-segmented and filiform, male antenna 15-segmented and filiform (
<figureCitation box="[160,242,935,962]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1924,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 6. a) Ceroptres cornigera lateral and b) dorsal habitus (type); c) C. ensiger lateral habitus, d) detail of mesopleuron and e) dorsal habitus (type); f) C. frondosae lateral and g) dorsal habitus (type); h) head and mesosoma of C. kovalevi in lateral view, i) lateral metasoma and j) head and mesosoma in dorsal view (type)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772846/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 6a</figureCitation>
); vertical carinae on the lower face incomplete, running from inner ventral margin of the toruli almost 2/3 of the lower face length and delimiting a depressed area that is bulged medially, forming a medial ridge (
<figureCitation box="[1318,1423,971,998]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1439,1464]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female faces of valid species of Ceroptres: a) C. catesbaei (type); b) C. cerri; c) C. clavicornis; d) C. confertus (type); e) C. cornigera (type); f) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. cornigera; g) head of C. cornigera in dorsal view; h) C. ensiger; i) C. frondosae (type); j) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. frondosae; k) head of C. frondosae in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772837/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 3e, f</figureCitation>
); mesoscutum strongly coriaceous with weak discontinuous transversal elements (
<figureCitation box="[1055,1138,1007,1034]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1924,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 6. a) Ceroptres cornigera lateral and b) dorsal habitus (type); c) C. ensiger lateral habitus, d) detail of mesopleuron and e) dorsal habitus (type); f) C. frondosae lateral and g) dorsal habitus (type); h) head and mesosoma of C. kovalevi in lateral view, i) lateral metasoma and j) head and mesosoma in dorsal view (type)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772846/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 6b</figureCitation>
); notauli almost complete, faint in the anterior 1/3 or before reaching the pronotal margin; median groove visible at most in the posterior 1/3 of the mesoscutum; mesoscutellum (
<figureCitation box="[570,654,1079,1106]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1924,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 6. a) Ceroptres cornigera lateral and b) dorsal habitus (type); c) C. ensiger lateral habitus, d) detail of mesopleuron and e) dorsal habitus (type); f) C. frondosae lateral and g) dorsal habitus (type); h) head and mesosoma of C. kovalevi in lateral view, i) lateral metasoma and j) head and mesosoma in dorsal view (type)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772846/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 6b</figureCitation>
) densely but weakly wrinkled, more strongly wrinkled laterally and posteriorly, interspaces strongly coriaceous; third metasomal tergum with an inconspicuous posterodorsal patch of micropunctures and subsequent terga very finely punctate; radial cell 2.7 times as long as wide; body mainly black. For more details on the morphology of this species, consult 
<bibRefCitation author="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A." box="[829,1083,1187,1213]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="625 - 631" refId="ref56807" refString="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A. (2002) Description of the sexual generation of Callirhytis quercuscornigera and a new inquiline (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae). Florida Entomologist, 85 (4), 625 - 631. https: // doi. org / 10.1653 / 0015 - 4040 (2002) 085 [0625: DOTSGO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">Melika &amp; Buss (2002)</bibRefCitation>
and the remarks section of this species (see below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1022,1258,1285]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,358,2041]" box="[199,1022,1258,1285]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1258,1285]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[359,419,1259,1285]" name="United States of America" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">USA</collectingCountry>
. Lexington, state of 
<collectingRegion box="[647,756,1259,1285]" country="United States of America" name="Kentucky" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Kentucky</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A." box="[771,1010,1259,1285]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="625 - 631" refId="ref56807" refString="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A. (2002) Description of the sexual generation of Callirhytis quercuscornigera and a new inquiline (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae). Florida Entomologist, 85 (4), 625 - 631. https: // doi. org / 10.1653 / 0015 - 4040 (2002) 085 [0625: DOTSGO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">Melika &amp; Buss 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,358,2041]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,1294,1321]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Biology</emphasis>
. Reared from stem and leaf galls of the asexual and sexual generations of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Osten-Sacken, 1862) (Melika &amp; Buss 2002)" authorityName="Melika &amp; Buss" authorityYear="2002" baseAuthorityName="Osten-Sacken" baseAuthorityYear="1862" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Callirhytis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quercuscornigera">
<emphasis box="[1113,1436,1295,1321]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Callirhytis quercuscornigera</emphasis>
(Osten-Sacken, 1862) (
<bibRefCitation author="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A." box="[410,647,1331,1357]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="625 - 631" refId="ref56807" refString="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A. (2002) Description of the sexual generation of Callirhytis quercuscornigera and a new inquiline (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae). Florida Entomologist, 85 (4), 625 - 631. https: // doi. org / 10.1653 / 0015 - 4040 (2002) 085 [0625: DOTSGO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">Melika &amp; Buss 2002</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
respectively, which associates with 
<taxonomicName authority="Muenchh." authorityName="Muenchh." box="[1062,1381,1331,1357]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="palustris">
<emphasis box="[1062,1261,1331,1357]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Quercus palustris</emphasis>
Muenchh.
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lobatae</emphasis>
section) and other red oaks (
<bibRefCitation author="Burks, B. D." box="[537,671,1367,1393]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1045 - 1107" refId="ref55625" refString="Burks, B. D. (1979) Superfamily Cynipoidea. In: Krombein, K. V., Hurd, P. D., Smith, D. R. &amp; Burks, B. D. (Eds.), Catalog of Hymenoptera in America north of Mexico. Vol. 1. Symphyta and Apocrita (Parasitica). Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, D. C., pp. 1045 - 1107." type="book chapter" year="1979">Burks 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A." box="[683,921,1367,1393]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="625 - 631" refId="ref56807" refString="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A. (2002) Description of the sexual generation of Callirhytis quercuscornigera and a new inquiline (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae). Florida Entomologist, 85 (4), 625 - 631. https: // doi. org / 10.1653 / 0015 - 4040 (2002) 085 [0625: DOTSGO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">Melika &amp; Buss 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,358,2041]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1403,1429]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[323,552,1403,1429]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[323,552,1403,1429]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ceroptres cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described from 
<specimenCount box="[908,957,1403,1429]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="male">18♂</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[1014,1063,1403,1429]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="female">18♀</specimenCount>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A." box="[1079,1379,1403,1430]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="625 - 631" refId="ref56807" refString="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A. (2002) Description of the sexual generation of Callirhytis quercuscornigera and a new inquiline (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae). Florida Entomologist, 85 (4), 625 - 631. https: // doi. org / 10.1653 / 0015 - 4040 (2002) 085 [0625: DOTSGO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">Melika &amp; Buss 2002: 629</bibRefCitation>
). We examined 
<specimenCount box="[267,302,1439,1465]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="female">3♀</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[357,392,1438,1465]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="male">5♂</specimenCount>
deposited in USNM, including the 
<typeStatus box="[791,893,1439,1465]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">holotype</typeStatus>
. According to G. Melika (pers. comm.), no mor- phological differences have been observed between specimens obtained from sexual and asexual galls.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,358,2041]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName box="[199,425,1511,1537]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[199,425,1511,1537]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ceroptres cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was characterized by 
<bibRefCitation author="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A." box="[669,974,1511,1538]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="625 - 631" refId="ref56807" refString="Melika, G. &amp; Buss, E. A. (2002) Description of the sexual generation of Callirhytis quercuscornigera and a new inquiline (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae). Florida Entomologist, 85 (4), 625 - 631. https: // doi. org / 10.1653 / 0015 - 4040 (2002) 085 [0625: DOTSGO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">Melika &amp; Buss (2002: 626)</bibRefCitation>
; however, after studying its 
<typeStatus box="[1284,1332,1511,1537]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">type</typeStatus>
material, we found some inconsistencies in the original description, and especially in the illustrations provided to characterize the species: (i) vertical carinae on the lower face are narrow and curved outwards in their distal half according to the illustrations, but in the 
<typeStatus box="[486,534,1619,1645]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">type</typeStatus>
material examined these carinae are somewhat broad and straight, not reaching the oral fovea; (ii) the specimens examined have a median ridge between the two vertical carinae (
<figureCitation box="[1267,1347,1655,1682]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1439,1464]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female faces of valid species of Ceroptres: a) C. catesbaei (type); b) C. cerri; c) C. clavicornis; d) C. confertus (type); e) C. cornigera (type); f) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. cornigera; g) head of C. cornigera in dorsal view; h) C. ensiger; i) C. frondosae (type); j) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. frondosae; k) head of C. frondosae in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772837/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 3f</figureCitation>
), which is not represented in the original illustrations nor commented on in the description; (iii) genae are expanded behind compound eyes in the original illustrations, but this trait has been exaggerated since genae are from very slightly to not expanded in the specimens examined (
<figureCitation box="[653,735,1763,1789]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1439,1464]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,265,1420]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female faces of valid species of Ceroptres: a) C. catesbaei (type); b) C. cerri; c) C. clavicornis; d) C. confertus (type); e) C. cornigera (type); f) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. cornigera; g) head of C. cornigera in dorsal view; h) C. ensiger; i) C. frondosae (type); j) detail of the median ridge in the lower face of C. frondosae; k) head of C. frondosae in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772837/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 3e</figureCitation>
); (iv) lastly, the mesoscutellum has a medial ridge between the scutellar foveae that reaches the mid of the mesoscutellum according to the original illustrations, but this ridge is absent in the specimens examined (
<figureCitation box="[542,624,1835,1862]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1924,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1433,166,1904]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 6. a) Ceroptres cornigera lateral and b) dorsal habitus (type); c) C. ensiger lateral habitus, d) detail of mesopleuron and e) dorsal habitus (type); f) C. frondosae lateral and g) dorsal habitus (type); h) head and mesosoma of C. kovalevi in lateral view, i) lateral metasoma and j) head and mesosoma in dorsal view (type)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772846/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 6b</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, POL:OOL:LOL and OOL/diameter lateral ocelli relations are not commented on in the original description.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,358,2041]" lastBlockId="26.[151,1437,153,395]" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName box="[199,428,1907,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[199,428,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ceroptres cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically almost identical to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ashmead, 1896" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[875,1207,1907,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis box="[875,894,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[909,1020,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">frondosae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ashmead, W. H." box="[1027,1207,1907,1933]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="179 - 234" refId="ref55364" refString="Ashmead, W. H. (1896) Descriptions of new parasitic Hymenoptera. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 23 (2), 179 - 234." type="journal article" year="1896">Ashmead, 1896</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, the few differences have already been commented on above (see the diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName box="[836,978,1943,1969]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[836,978,1943,1969]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[1001,1227,1943,1969]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[1001,1227,1943,1969]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ceroptres cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was obtained both from leaf (sexual) and stem (asexual) galls, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[723,868,1979,2005]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis box="[723,868,1979,2005]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. frondosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
emerged from galls on axillary leaf-buds (see the biology section of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[363,507,2015,2041]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis box="[363,507,2015,2041]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. frondosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), which could correspond to the sexual form of the gall maker; also, these species were described from adjacent states (
<collectingRegion box="[575,686,153,179]" country="United States of America" name="Kentucky" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Kentucky</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[745,847,153,179]" country="United States of America" name="Missouri" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Missouri</collectingRegion>
, respectively). However, both specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
obtained from sexual galls and those obtained from asexual galls of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melika &amp; Buss" authorityYear="2002" baseAuthorityName="Osten-Sacken" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[1007,1333,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Callirhytis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quercuscornigera">
<emphasis box="[1007,1333,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Callirhytis quercuscornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the same ocellar ratios as the 
<typeStatus box="[439,487,225,251]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">type</typeStatus>
material examined (all obtained from asexual galls) and also according to G. Melika (who measured specimens obtained from sexual galls, pers. comm.), thus suggesting this species is distinct from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[151,294,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis box="[151,294,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. frondosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, we here consider that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[676,819,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frondosae">
<emphasis box="[676,819,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. frondosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[873,1015,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Ceroptres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[873,1015,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are different species, even though we do not rule out the possibility that they may be the same species and that the differences observed are indicative of intraspecific variation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
